<DOC><DOCNO> AP890629-0213 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2345EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Nuclear     06-29 0174</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Britain-Nuclear,0179</SECOND><HEAD>Labor's Kinnock Says Anti-Nuclear Policy A Loser</HEAD><DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Opposition leader Neil Kinnock onThursday attacked Britain's biggest union, the transport workers,for continuing to support unilateral nuclear disarmament, avote-losing policy his Labor Party is giving up.   ``You voted to meet the change in the world by making nochange,'' Kinnock told a conference of the 1.3 million-memberTransport and General Workers' Union.   Kinnock is a member of the left-led union, which voted on Tuesdayto keep its anti-nuclear policy.   Kinnock, a longtime anti-nuclear campaigner, said Labor wouldnever win power again if it kept the anti-nuclear policy it adoptedin 1981. In a policy overhaul announced in May, Labor droppedunilateral nuclear disarmament.   The policy was cited as a key factor in Labor's 1983 and 1987election defeats by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservatives.   Kinnock, 47, joined Britain's Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament asa teen-ager. He says he changed his mind because superpower nucleararms reduction agreements and the possibility of more deals havealtered the circumstances.</TEXT></DOC>